Model diagnostics (Assumptions of Linear Regression)

#par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit1)

#1. Assumption of Existance of a linear relationship

cor(medv, lstat)
## [1] -0.7376627
plot(lstat, medv, main = "Scatterplot of lstat vs medv", xlab = "lstat", ylab = "medv")
abline(lm(medv ~ lstat), col = "red")  # Add regression line

#2. Assumption of Normality

## normality of residuals
shapiro.test(residuals(fit1))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  residuals(fit1)
## W = 0.87857, p-value < 2.2e-16
# histogram of residuals with normal and kdensity curves
hist(residuals(fit1), freq=FALSE)
lines(density(residuals(fit1)), col="red")

# qq plot
qqnorm(residuals(fit1))
qqline(residuals(fit1))

#3. homoscedasticity (scale-location plot)
plot(fitted(fit1), sqrt(abs(residuals(fit1))))

#4. linearity (residuals vs fitted values)
plot(fitted(fit1), residuals(fit1))

#5. independence
plot(residuals(fit1))

  1. LINEAR DISCRIMINANT ANALYIS (LDA)

LDA is a dimensionality reduction and classification technique that finds the linear combinations of features that best separate two or more classes by maximizing the between-class variance while minimizing the within-class variance.

  1. K-NEAREST NEIGHBORS (KNN)
library(class)
require(ISLR)
data(Smarket)

?knn
attach(Smarket)
# create a train and test set
Xlog <- cbind(Lag1, Lag2)
train <- Year < 2005

knn.pred <- knn(Xlog[train,], Xlog[!train,], Direction[train], k=1)

#confusion matrix
table(knn.pred, Direction[!train])
##         
## knn.pred Down Up
##     Down   43 58
##     Up     68 83
#accuracy
mean(knn.pred == Direction[!train])
## [1] 0.5
# using k=3
knn.pred <- knn(Xlog[train,], Xlog[!train,], Direction[train], k=3)

#confusion matrix
table(knn.pred, Direction[!train])
##         
## knn.pred Down Up
##     Down   48 54
##     Up     63 87
#accuracy
mean(knn.pred == Direction[!train])
## [1] 0.5357143
# plot the decision boundary
plot(Lag2 ~ Lag1, data=Smarket, col=knn.pred)

LOOCV

glm.fit <- glm(mpg ~ horsepower, data=Auto)
cv.glm(Auto, glm.fit)$delta
## [1] 24.23151 24.23114
loocv <- function(fit){
  h = lm.influence(fit)$h
  mean((residuals(fit)/(1-h))^2)
  
  }
loocv(glm.fit)
## [1] 24.23151
cv.error <- rep(0, 5)
degree <- 1:5

for(d in degree){
  glm.fit <- glm(mpg ~ poly(horsepower, d), data=Auto)
  cv.error[d] <- loocv(glm.fit)
}

plot(degree, cv.error, type="b")

# 10 fold cross validation
cv.error10 <- rep(0, 5)

for(d in degree){
  glm.fit <- glm(mpg ~ poly(horsepower, d), data=Auto)
  cv.error10[d] <- cv.glm(Auto, glm.fit, K=10)$delta[1]
}

plot(degree, cv.error10, type="b")

lines(degree, cv.error, col="red")
